{"id": "2026-07-12-news-iran-strikes-five-gulf-states-and-closes-strait", "date": "2026-07-12", "stream": "news", "headline": "Iran strikes five Gulf states and closes Strait of Hormuz as US launches third round of strikes", "summary": "Iran attacked US targets in Oman, Qatar, Kuwait, Bahrain and Jordan and closed the Strait of Hormuz as US CENTCOM completed a third round of strikes (300+ targets over three nights) with the ceasefire declared over.", "url": "https://www.centcom.mil/MEDIA/PUBLIC-RELEASES/Article/4540919/us-forces-finish-latest-round-of-strikes-against-iran/", "source_domain": "centcom.mil", "tier": "T1", "tags": ["new source", "via snippet"], "topics": ["geopolitics"], "importance": 3, "display_body": "Iran struck US military targets across five Gulf states and formally closed the Strait of Hormuz overnight into Sunday 12 July, as US Central Command completed a third round of strikes on Iran in a week. The IRGC (Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps) said it hit US bases and facilities in Oman (logistics and refuelling sites at the port of Duqm), Kuwait (a Patriot air-defence system, an ammunition depot and a radar site), Bahrain (a communications and radar site), Jordan (ballistic missiles against Prince Hassan airbase) and Qatar, where three people including a child were wounded by falling shrapnel from intercepted attacks. Iran declared the strait, which carries roughly 20% of the world's traded energy, closed until the end of US interference in the region. CENTCOM said its latest round struck about 140 targets and that more than 300 were hit over three nights, triggered by an IRGC attack on the Cyprus-flagged container ship M/V GFS Galaxy. President Trump declared the ceasefire over on Wednesday 8 July; Iran's new Supreme Leader Mojtaba Khamenei has vowed to avenge his father's killing.", "why": "A closed Hormuz and simultaneous strikes on the Gulf monarchies that host US bases mark the sharpest escalation since the February conflict began, a direct threat to global oil and LNG flows and to the fragile diplomacy Oman and Qatar had been brokering.", "thread_id": "2026-06-20-cyber-papers-iran-closes-strait-of-hormuz-again-over-israeli", "first_seen_date": "2026-06-20", "event_date": "2026-07-12", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": ""}
{"id": "2026-07-12-news-us-senator-lindsey-graham-trump-ally-and-iran-ha", "date": "2026-07-12", "stream": "news", "headline": "US Senator Lindsey Graham, Trump ally and Iran hawk, dies at 71", "summary": "South Carolina Republican Senator Lindsey Graham, a leading foreign-policy hawk and Trump ally, died on 11 July at 71 after a brief sudden illness.", "url": "https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/7/12/us-senator-lindsey-graham-passes-away", "source_domain": "aljazeera.com", "tier": "T2", "tags": [], "topics": ["politics", "world"], "importance": 2, "display_body": "US Senator Lindsey Graham, a leading Republican foreign-policy hawk and close ally of President Trump, died on Saturday evening, 11 July, at 71 after a brief and sudden illness, his office said in a statement on Sunday. The South Carolina senator was first elected to the Senate in 2002 and re-elected three times, and most recently chaired the Senate Budget Committee. A staunch supporter of the 2003 Iraq invasion and one of the chamber's most vocal advocates for military action against Iran, he had backed the current US campaign; Israel's Defence Ministry said it was saddened by his death. Once an outspoken Trump critic who dropped out of the 2016 Republican primary early, he later became one of the president's closest congressional allies.", "why": "Graham's death removes one of the Senate's most influential hawks at the moment the US is deepening its war with Iran, and narrows the Republican majority.", "thread_id": "2026-07-12-news-us-senator-lindsey-graham-trump-ally-and-iran-ha", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-12", "event_date": "2026-07-11", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": ""}
{"id": "2026-07-12-news-former-qatar-emir-sheikh-hamad-bin-khalifa-al-th", "date": "2026-07-12", "stream": "news", "headline": "Former Qatar Emir Sheikh Hamad bin Khalifa Al Thani, founder of Al Jazeera, dies at 74", "summary": "Sheikh Hamad bin Khalifa Al Thani, the former Qatari emir who founded Al Jazeera and abdicated to his son Tamim in 2013, died on 12 July at 74.", "url": "https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/7/12/former-emir-of-qatar-sheikh-hamad-bin-khalifa-al-thani-dies-at-74", "source_domain": "aljazeera.com", "tier": "T2", "tags": [], "topics": ["world"], "importance": 2, "display_body": "Sheikh Hamad bin Khalifa Al Thani, the former emir who reshaped Qatar into a global player and founded Al Jazeera, died on Sunday 12 July at 74. Known as the Father Emir, he came to power in 1995 and ruled until 2013, when in a rare abdication for a Gulf hereditary ruler he handed the throne to his son, the current Emir Sheikh Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani. His tenure saw the launch of the Al Jazeera news channel in 1996, Qatar's first permanent constitution in 2004, and the introduction of municipal elections in which women could vote and stand. Condolences poured in from across the region, including Egyptian President el-Sisi and UAE President Mohamed bin Zayed.", "why": "Hamad's bet on outsized diplomacy, media and gas wealth is the template for Qatar's current role as a mediator, including in the very Gulf crisis now unfolding around it.", "thread_id": "2026-07-12-news-former-qatar-emir-sheikh-hamad-bin-khalifa-al-th", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-12", "event_date": "2026-07-12", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": ""}
{"id": "2026-07-12-news-wildfire-in-andalusia-kills-12-as-european-heatw", "date": "2026-07-12", "stream": "news", "headline": "Wildfire in Andalusia kills 12 as European heatwave intensifies", "summary": "A wildfire near Almeria in southern Spain has killed at least 12 with 23 missing, though authorities said on 12 July the flames were no longer spreading, amid a Europe-wide heatwave.", "url": "https://www.srf.ch/news/international/feuer-im-sueden-spaniens-zwoelf-tote-bei-waldbrand-flammen-breiten-sich-nicht-weiter-aus", "source_domain": "srf.ch", "tier": "T2", "tags": ["single-source"], "topics": ["world"], "importance": 2, "display_body": "A wildfire in Andalusia, southern Spain, has killed at least 12 people with 23 still reported missing, though authorities said on Sunday 12 July the flames were no longer spreading. The fire, around the municipalities of Los Gallardos and Bedar some 70km northeast of Almeria, has destroyed roughly 7,000 hectares of forest and scrub; some 500 firefighters, soldiers and other responders remain deployed, and Andalusian regional president Juanma Moreno said weaker winds and higher humidity had aided the effort, with hopes of full containment within hours. The blaze is one front of a heatwave gripping much of Europe: France has triggered its emergency plan in the departements under the highest heat alert, and the same system is driving Switzerland's federal heat warning.", "why": "The death toll makes this one of Spain's deadliest recent wildfires, and underscores how the intensifying European heatwave is turning routine summer heat into a lethal, cross-border hazard.", "thread_id": "2026-07-10-news-wildfire-in-southern-spain-kills-at-least-11-wit", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-10", "event_date": "2026-07-09", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": ""}
{"id": "2026-07-12-news-switzerland-out-of-world-cup-after-3-1-extra-tim", "date": "2026-07-12", "stream": "news", "headline": "Switzerland out of World Cup after 3-1 extra-time loss to Argentina and contested Embolo red card", "summary": "Defending champions Argentina beat Switzerland 3-1 in extra time in the World Cup quarterfinal on 11 July after Breel Embolo was sent off via VAR for simulation.", "url": "https://www.letemps.ch/articles/une-suisse-admirable-et-un-peu-naive-tombe-en-quart-de-finale-face-a-l-argentine", "source_domain": "letemps.ch", "tier": "T2", "tags": [], "topics": ["switzerland"], "importance": 1, "display_body": "Switzerland's World Cup run ended on Saturday night, 11 July, with a 3-1 extra-time quarterfinal defeat to defending champions Argentina, in a match soured by a contested red card. Argentina led through Alexis Mac Allister in the 10th minute before Dan Ndoye equalised for Switzerland in the 67th; four minutes later, forward Breel Embolo was sent off after a VAR (video assistant referee) review ruled he had simulated contact, the referee initially booking Argentina's Leandro Paredes before rescinding it and carding Embolo, who was already on a yellow. Reduced to ten players at 1-1, Switzerland conceded twice in extra time as Argentina advanced to a semifinal against England.", "why": "It is the deepest Swiss run in a men's World Cup in decades, and the disputed dismissal will dominate the national conversation for days.", "thread_id": "2026-07-12-news-switzerland-out-of-world-cup-after-3-1-extra-tim", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-12", "event_date": "2026-07-11", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": ""}
